# Hiring Philosophy

Hiring is the highest-leverage thing I do. A great hire raises the floor for everyone. A wrong hire — especially at senior levels — costs the team more than the role is worth.

## What I'm looking for

**People who own things.** Not people who complete tasks. There's a meaningful difference between someone who closes tickets and someone who takes responsibility for an outcome. I want the latter.

**People who communicate clearly under pressure.** When things are hard — and they will be — I need people who can stay clear-headed, say what's true, and ask for help when they need it.

**People who make the people around them better.** Brilliant individuals who operate in silos don't interest me. I want people who share what they know, give real feedback, and pull others up.

**Curiosity.** I want people who ask why. Who read things. Who have opinions and can defend them. Who get genuinely excited about learning something new.

## How I interview

I'm not interested in gotcha questions or whiteboard theater. I want to understand how you actually think. I'll ask you about real situations — what happened, what you did, what you'd do differently. I'll push on your answers. That's not hostility; that's how I understand how you operate.

I also pay attention to how you treat everyone you interact with in the process — not just the hiring manager.

## What I won't compromise on

Culture is not a vibe. It's a set of behaviors. I will not hire someone who is technically exceptional but caustic, dismissive, or dishonest. The cost is always higher than it looks.

## On diversity

I believe diverse teams build better products. This isn't a talking point — it's something I actively work at. That means examining where we source candidates, how we structure interviews to reduce bias, and whether our bar is consistent across every person who walks through the door.
